2022 was all about self-improvement. The year where I realised Im not necessarily good at one particular thing. This thought bugged me for a while, when I picked trading as a skill to learn. An astounding skill for a 15 year old isnt it? Can you imagine how pathetic the feeling is when your family is struggling to make the ends meet and theres not a single thing youre doing about it. I endured self-pity. I knew I couldnt just sit around while my mom rains sweat and tears. In my desperation to earn money, my friend introduced me to trading. Sitting in front of the charts for 8 hours daily for at least 3 months made me realize, if theres anything thats going to change my familys situation, its trading. I have never looked back once after I started my journey. The early days were rough. I had doubts if I would be able to make it. There was a lot at stake but that didnt hold me back. The first 3 months of rigorous hunger to learn was needed just to realize trading isnt about playing with numbers. As you dive deeper and deeper into it you realize trading is a psychological warfare. I have never experienced my emotions taking over my decisions more than in trading. It has not only helped me learn a skill but also helped me to be mentally strong. I knew I couldnt just quit and live a mediocre life again. The next month was rough than ever. I ran out of beginners luck. When I started thinking maybe I am good at it, I got reality checked by the very skill itself. I lost all the motivation to learn further. But if theres anything Im good at, it has to be building habits. I knew I can make past this because when the motivation fails, discipline prevails. There was nothing to lose. Every day I kept progressing. I failed, I tripped, I had some huge losses but it wasnt enough to make me stop. I am glad I dont have that cushion to fall on from my family. It hits hard when you fall on the floor, but I think those are the situations where strongest people are created. This gives me enough motivation to keep me going in other aspects of my life as well.

freedom is a concept that has been debated throughout history. some argye that it is an inherent right of all individuals while others argue that it is something that must be earned or granted by governing authority. In many ways, the idea of freedom is a myth because it is something that can never truly be attained and individuals are ultimately constrained by various factors such as social norms, laws and economic systems. one reason why freedom is a myth is that it is often define differently but different people. for some freedom may the ability to speak ones mind without fear of repression for others it may mean the freedom to pursue ones own goals and aspirations without interference. these different definitions can lead to confusion and disagreement about what freedom truly means. furthermore even in democratic society where the citizens have the freedom to vote, the power and influence of the wealthy and the media can shape the political and social environment in ways that limit the freedom of the general population. for example almost all news media agency this result in censorship and bias in the news that is reported, potentially limiting the freedom of the general population to access accurate information. economic systems also play a role in the limiting freedom. In capitalist societies for example United States of America, Germany, individuals are often constrained by their economic status and are not truely free to make choices that would improve their lives if they lack the financial means to do so. additionally the concentration of wealth in a small number of individuals and corporations can limit the freedom of the majority of citizens. The concept of freedom is often used to justify Actions that are actually harmful to others. for example some argue that individuals should be free to own guns while others argue that this freedom puts others at risk. similarly some are argue that individuals should be free to engage in hate speech while others argue that this freedom harms marginalized groups. these examples illustrate l the concept of freedom can be used to justify actions that are actually harmful to others

"Salvatore" is a short story by W. Somerset Maugham, which tells the story of a young Sicilian man named Salvatore. Salvatore is portrayed as a simple and honest peasant who is deeply in love with his childhood sweetheart, Rosa. He is a hard worker who is determined to provide for Rosa and their future family. He is also deeply devoted to his Catholic faith, and his actions are guided by his belief in God and the teachings of the Church. On the other hand, the spider in the poem "The Spider and the Fly" by Mary Howitt is portrayed as a cunning and deceitful creature. The spider is depicted as using clever and persuasive language to lure the unsuspecting fly into its web, with the intention of killing and eating it. The spider is portrayed as a predator, using its wits and charm to trap its prey. In terms of character, Salvatore is portrayed as a virtuous and hardworking individual, while the spider is portrayed as a deceptive and manipulative predator. Salvatore's actions are guided by his love for a girl and his faith, while the spider's actions are driven by its hunger and need to survive. Salvatore is a sympathetic and relatable character, while the spider is portrayed as a villain. In terms of themes, the story of Salvatore explores themes of love, faith, and the struggle to survive and provide for one's family. The poem "The Spider and the Fly" explores themes of temptation, deception, and the dangers of being lured into a false sense of security. Both characters teaches us a moral lesson: Salvatore teaches us the importance of hard work, perseverance, and faith in the face of adversity, while the spider portrays and makes us aware of one who uses charm and persuasion to manipulate and deceive others. CONCLUSION Overall, Salvatore and the spider from the poem "The Spider and the Fly" are vastly different characters, with different motivations and personalities. While Salvatore is portrayed as a sympathetic and relatable character, the spider is portrayed as a villain. Salvatore's actions are motivated by a desire to protect and provide for his family, while the spider's actions are motivated by a desire to feed and survive. Their relationship with nature is also very different. Salvatore is in tune with nature while the spider is using nature to its advantage. The themes and moral lessons in both story and poem also differ, with Salvatore's story exploring themes of love, faith, and the struggle to survive, while the poem explores themes of temptation, deception, and the dangers of being lured into a false sense of security.

The social issue that you would like to address and why

According to me, mental health is an essential thread that weaves through our thoughts, emotions and actions. Yet, the silence surrounding mental health issues often conceals the struggles that individuals face. My family's story is a reminder of mental health awareness and access to care, as my father, aka a pillar of strength, surrendered to the silent battles within his mind. Dad was the essential provider, a hardworking entrepreneur who poured his heart and soul into his business. His dedication was evident in the long hours spent at work and an unwavering commitment to our well-being. However, beneath the surface of his seemingly robust exterior, something was not right. His mental health struggles were concealed behind his stoic nature. Dad never spoke about the burdens he carries. It was only after his tragic passing, a result of the mental stress originating from his business, that we realized the truth. In the aftermath, I was told that he passed away due to a car accident but his prescriptions from a psychiatrist that I found said otherwise. This experience highlights the urgent need for mental health awareness and accessible care. The stigma attached to mental health issues played a pivotal role in my father's silence. In a society that often prizes strength as the ability to weather storms in silence, seeking help for mental health concerns is perceived as a sign of weakness. Breaking down these societal barriers and fostering open conversations about mental health are crucial steps toward a better world. In my research, approximately 1 in 4 people worldwide will experience a mental health issue at some point in their lives. This underscores the universality of mental health concerns and the need for a collective effort to address them. One solution to this problem lies in amplifying mental health education, ensuring that it reaches every community. By incorporating mental health awareness programs into the school curriculum, we can cultivate a society that recognizes the importance of emotional well-being. Personally, being a great friend to those in need would leave a great impact on other people's lives. Making them realize that there is so much more to the world than they whine about is what makes me the therapist friend of the group. I am a firm believer in the quote "There are no hopeless situations, only people who have lost hope" and I stand to live by it.

Ans . Cell Theory Cell Theory is a fundamental concept in biology that describes the properties and functions of cells, which are the basic units of life. The theory was developed in the mid-19th century by scientists such as Matthias Schleiden, Theodor Schwann, and Rudolf Virchow. It is based on three main principles: 1. All Living Organisms Are Composed of Cells: This principle states that all living things, whether unicellular (like bacteria) or multicellular (like plants and animals), are made up of cells. Cells are the smallest units of life that can carry out all necessary life processes. 2. The Cell Is the Basic Unit of Life: Cells are the fundamental building blocks of all living organisms. They are the smallest units that can perform all life functions, including metabolism, growth, and reproduction. This principle emphasizes that the properties of cells determine the characteristics of the organism as a whole. 3. All Cells Arise from Pre-existing Cells: This principle, proposed by Rudolf Virchow, states that new cells are produced only from the division of existing cells. This concept refutes the idea of spontaneous generation and underscores the continuity of life through cellular reproduction.
